hmNetPPPBaseIPAddr.name: hmNetPPPBaseIPAddr
hmNetPPPBaseIPAddr.description: Base address of the IP address range used by the point-to-point protocol. The IP addresses hmNetPPPBaseAddress..hmNetPPPBaseAddress+4 are assigned to the client machines attached to management agents 1..5. The management agents can be reached using addresses hmNetPPPBaseAddress+10..hmNetPPPBaseAddress+14. Changing this variable on one agent automatically updates the value on the other agents in the same chassis.

hmNetPPPNetMask.name: hmNetPPPNetMask
hmNetPPPNetMask.description: Subnet mask used by the point-to-point protocol. Changing this variable on one agent automatically updates the value on the other agents in the same chassis.

hmNetAction.name: hmNetAction
hmNetAction.description: This object, when read, always returns a value of other(1). Setting the object to activate(2) causes a reconfiguration of the IP protocol stack with the current values of hmNetLocalIPAddr, hmNetGatewayIPAddr and hmNetMask.

hmNetVlanID.name: hmNetVlanID
hmNetVlanID.description: Vlan ID of the IP protocol stack. If the value is 0, Traffic from all Vlans is accepted. Every other value means that only traffic of the appropriate Vlan is accepted and outgoing traffic uses this Vlan ID.

hmNetLocalPhysAddrRange.name: hmNetLocalPhysAddrRange
hmNetLocalPhysAddrRange.description: The number of MAC addresses reserved for this device, starting from hmNetLocalPhysAddr.

hmNetVlanPriority.name: hmNetVlanPriority
hmNetVlanPriority.description: Vlan Priority which is used in management replies.

hmNetIpDscpPriority.name: hmNetIpDscpPriority
hmNetIpDscpPriority.description: IP DSCP value which is used in management replies.

hmNetACDStatus.name: hmNetACDStatus
hmNetACDStatus.description: Sets the mode of the ip address conflict detection mechanism on this device. enable(1): Both active and passive detection are active. disable(2): No detection takes place. activeDetectionOnly(3): During configuration of a local ip address the device actively probes the network for this ip address. passiveDetectionOnly(4): The device listens passively on the network if another device with an already locally configured ip address appears. In this case the own ip address is actively defended by transmitting gratituous arp's.

hmNetACDOngoingProbeStatus.name: hmNetACDOngoingProbeStatus
hmNetACDOngoingProbeStatus.description: If enabled, the device sends periodic arp probes.

hmNetACDDelay.name: hmNetACDDelay
hmNetACDDelay.description: The maximum detection delay time in milliseconds. Time gap between arp probes.

hmNetACDReleaseDelay.name: hmNetACDReleaseDelay
hmNetACDReleaseDelay.description: Delay in seconds to the next arp probe cycle after an ip address conflict was detected.

hmNetACDMaxProtection.name: hmNetACDMaxProtection
hmNetACDMaxProtection.description: Maximum number of frequent address protections.

hmNetACDProtectInterval.name: hmNetACDProtectInterval
hmNetACDProtectInterval.description: Delay in milliseconds between two protections.

hmNetACDFaultState.name: hmNetACDFaultState
hmNetACDFaultState.description: true(1) if an active address conflict is detected. false(2) if no present address conflict.

hmNetACDAddrTable.name: hmNetACDAddrTable
hmNetACDAddrTable.description: This table contains address conflict detection information on the local system known to this agent.

hmNetACDAddrEntry.name: hmNetACDAddrEntry
hmNetACDAddrEntry.description: IP Address conflict detection information about a particular address on the local system kown to this agent. There may be multiple addresses configured on the system. Entries may be created and deleted in this table by the agent.

hmNetACDTimeMark.name: hmNetACDTimeMark
hmNetACDTimeMark.description: A TimeFilter for this entry. See the TimeFilter textual convention in IETF RFC 2021 and http://www.ietf.org/IESG/Implementations/RFC2021-Implementation.txt to see how TimeFilter works.

hmNetACDAddrSubtype.name: hmNetACDAddrSubtype
hmNetACDAddrSubtype.description: The type of management address identifier encoding used in the associated 'hmNetACDAddr' object.

hmNetACDAddr.name: hmNetACDAddr
hmNetACDAddr.description: The string value used to identify the management address component associated with the local system.

hmNetACDMAC.name: hmNetACDMAC
hmNetACDMAC.description: The physical address of the device that was detected causing the ip address conflict.

hmNetACDIfId.name: hmNetACDIfId
hmNetACDIfId.description: The integer value used to identify the interface number on the local system where the ip address conflict was detected.

hmNetHiDiscoveryStatus.name: hmNetHiDiscoveryStatus
hmNetHiDiscoveryStatus.description: Enables/disables the HiDiscovery protocol on this device. This protocol allows a remote host to detect devices without an ip configuration. It also allows the host to set ip parameters, like the ip address, the netmask and the gateway address. If only detection and no configuration is allowed set this object to readOnly(3).

hmNetSNTPStatus.name: hmNetSNTPStatus
hmNetSNTPStatus.description: Enables/disables the Simple Network Time Protocol on this device.

hmNetSNTPServer.name: hmNetSNTPServer
hmNetSNTPServer.description: The IP Address of an external Time Server.

hmNetSNTPTime.name: hmNetSNTPTime
hmNetSNTPTime.description: The time in seconds since 01/01/1900 UTC.

hmNetSNTPLocalOffset.name: hmNetSNTPLocalOffset
hmNetSNTPLocalOffset.description: The difference between local time and UTC in minutes.

hmNetSNTPServer2.name: hmNetSNTPServer2
hmNetSNTPServer2.description: IP address of a secondary (backup) time server.

hmNetSNTPAcceptBroadcasts.name: hmNetSNTPAcceptBroadcasts
hmNetSNTPAcceptBroadcasts.description: This MIB variable specifies whether SNTP broadcasts will be allowed to synchronize the local clock. If hmNetSNTPStatus is enabled, this variable will be ignored and broadcasts will not set the local clock.

hmNetSNTPAnycastAddr.name: hmNetSNTPAnycastAddr
hmNetSNTPAnycastAddr.description: Destination address for SNTP broadcasts. A broadcast, multicast or unicast address may be specified. Setting the address to 0.0.0.0 disables SNTP broadcasts.

hmNetSNTPAnycastInterval.name: hmNetSNTPAnycastInterval
hmNetSNTPAnycastInterval.description: Interval of SNTP broadcast messages in seconds.

hmNetSNTPOperStatus.name: hmNetSNTPOperStatus
hmNetSNTPOperStatus.description: Operational status of the SNTP sub-system. The value is a bit mask: 1 local system clock synchronized 2 SNTP loop detected 4 generic error 8 once synced, client disabled 100 server 1 not synchronized 200 server 1 bad protocol version 400 server 1 not responding 10000 server 2 not synchronized 20000 server 2 bad protocol version 40000 server 2 not responding (Note that all values are hexadecimal.)

hmNetSNTPTimeAdjustThreshold.name: hmNetSNTPTimeAdjustThreshold
hmNetSNTPTimeAdjustThreshold.description: The threshold in milli-seconds whether to decide to set the received SNTP time directly to the local clock or not. If the hmNetSNTPTimeAdjustThreshold value is 0, the received SNTP time will be set directly to the local clock every time a SNTP message is received. If the difference between the local clock time and the received SNTP time is fewer than the hmNetSNTPTimeAdjustThreshold value, the local clock will not be set. If the difference between the local clock time and the received SNTP time is equal or larger than the hmNetSNTPTimeAdjustThreshold value, the local clock will be set.

hmNetSNTPOnceAtStartup.name: hmNetSNTPOnceAtStartup
hmNetSNTPOnceAtStartup.description: If enabled, SNTP ist automaticaly disabled after once synchronized to an SNTP Server.

hmNetSNTPServerOnlyIfSync.name: hmNetSNTPServerOnlyIfSync
hmNetSNTPServerOnlyIfSync.description: The SNTP server is enabled only if synchronized to another external time reference. (e.g. SNTP or PTP)

hmNetSNTPServerStatus.name: hmNetSNTPServerStatus
hmNetSNTPServerStatus.description: Enables/disables the SNTP server on this device if hmNetSNTPStatus is enabled.

hmNetSNTPClientStatus.name: hmNetSNTPClientStatus
hmNetSNTPClientStatus.description: Enables/disables the SNTP client on this device if hmNetSNTPStatus is enabled.

hmNetNTPServer1AddrType.name: hmNetNTPServer1AddrType
hmNetNTPServer1AddrType.description: Address type for server 1. Currently, only ipv4 is supported.

hmNetNTPServer1Address.name: hmNetNTPServer1Address
hmNetNTPServer1Address.description: The address of the first external time server.

hmNetNTPServer2AddrType.name: hmNetNTPServer2AddrType
hmNetNTPServer2AddrType.description: Address type for server 2. Currently, only ipv4 is supported.

hmNetNTPServer2Address.name: hmNetNTPServer2Address
hmNetNTPServer2Address.description: The address of the second external time server.

hmNetNTPSyncInterval.name: hmNetNTPSyncInterval
hmNetNTPSyncInterval.description: NTP synchronisation interval in seconds. NTP will round down the value to a power of 2. The protocol will use an interval between the rounded value and the next power of 2.

hmNetNTPAnycastAddrType.name: hmNetNTPAnycastAddrType
hmNetNTPAnycastAddrType.description: Address type for anycasts. Currently, only ipv4 is supported.

hmNetNTPAnycastAddress.name: hmNetNTPAnycastAddress
hmNetNTPAnycastAddress.description: Destination address for NTP broadcasts. A broadcast, multicast or unicast address may be specified. Setting the address to 0.0.0.0 disables NTP broadcasts.

hmNetNTPAnycastInterval.name: hmNetNTPAnycastInterval
hmNetNTPAnycastInterval.description: Interval of NTP broadcast messages in seconds. NTP will round down the value to a power of 2.

hmNetNTPStatusText.name: hmNetNTPStatusText
hmNetNTPStatusText.description: Operational status of the NTP sub-system.

hmNetNTPStatusCode.name: hmNetNTPStatusCode
hmNetNTPStatusCode.description: Operational status of the NTP sub-system. The value is a bit mask: 1 local system clock synchronized 2 generic error (see hmNetNTPStatusText) 100 server 1 not synchronized 200 server 1 protocol error 400 server 1 not responding 800 server 1 synchronization in progress 10000 server 2 not synchronized 20000 server 2 protocol error 40000 server 2 not responding 80000 server 2 synchronization in progress (Note that all values are hexadecimal.)

hmNetPTPEnable.name: hmNetPTPEnable
hmNetPTPEnable.description: Enable or disable the Precision Time Protocol on this node.

hmNetPTPAction.name: hmNetPTPAction
hmNetPTPAction.description: Initialize the PTP Clock. Value 2: The specification initialization set shall be used. Value 3: The initialization set stored in nonvolatile storage for recovery after a power fail shall be used. Value 1: no action. In GET operations the variable always returns other(1)

hmNetPTPClockMode.name: hmNetPTPClockMode
hmNetPTPClockMode.description: This members value shall indicate which clock mode is used. The ptp-mode-boundary-clock mode specifies the mode as described in the IEEE1588 standard. In the 'ptp-mode-simple-ptp' mode the device only accepts PTP sync messages, sets the time directly and no BMC algorithm will run. If the clock mode is changed, PTP will be initialized.

hmNetPTPSlavePort.name: hmNetPTPSlavePort
hmNetPTPSlavePort.description: This members value shall indicate the slave port where this clock is synchronized in the ptp-mode-static-boundary-clock mode. The default value is 0 (i.e. clock is grandmaster).

hmNetPTPIsSynchronized.name: hmNetPTPIsSynchronized
hmNetPTPIsSynchronized.description: If the clock is synchronized to the current Master this object is set to true. Otherwise it is set to false. The clock sets this object to true, if the offset (ns) to the current Master is less than hmNetPTPSyncLowerBound. The clock sets this object to false, if the offset (ns) to the current Master is bigger than hmNetPTPSyncUpperBound.

hmNetPTPSyncLowerBound.name: hmNetPTPSyncLowerBound
hmNetPTPSyncLowerBound.description: This object defines when the hmNetPTPIsSynchronized object is set to true. If the absolute value of the offset is smaller than hmNetPTPSyncLowerBound, the hmNetPTPIsSynchronized is set true. The value is interpreted as nanoseconds.

hmNetPTPSyncUpperBound.name: hmNetPTPSyncUpperBound
hmNetPTPSyncUpperBound.description: This object defines when the hmNetPTPIsSynchronized object is set to false. If the absolute value of the offset is bigger than hmNetPTPSyncUpperBound, the hmNetPTPIsSynchronized is set false. The value is interpreted as nanoseconds.

hmNetPTPClockStratum.name: hmNetPTPClockStratum
hmNetPTPClockStratum.description: The clock stratum, or stratum number, describes one measure of the quality of a clock. Each clock shall be characterized by a stratum number to be used by the best master clock algorithm as one parameter of clock quality. A clock stratum of 1 is the best, where the default clock stratum is 255.

hmNetPTPClockIdentifier.name: hmNetPTPClockIdentifier
hmNetPTPClockIdentifier.description: The clock identifier indicates the nature and expected absolute accuracy and epoch of a given clock. Possible values are ATOM, GPS, NTP, HAND, INIT, DFLT. Values with less characters than the maximum allowed length will be padded with zero characters.

hmNetPTPClockVariance.name: hmNetPTPClockVariance
hmNetPTPClockVariance.description: The clock variance reflects the inherent characteristics of the clock. It is an estimate of the local clock from a linear time scale when it is not synchronized to another PTP clock using the PTP protocol.

hmNetPTPPreferredMaster.name: hmNetPTPPreferredMaster
hmNetPTPPreferredMaster.description: A clock may be administratively designated as part of a preferred master clock set. This creates a set of clocks that will be favored over those not so designated in the selection of master clocks within a subdomain. The purpose of this designation is to allow users to specify a clock that will remain master in the presence of disconnection or connection of other clocks.

hmNetPTPSyncInterval.name: hmNetPTPSyncInterval
hmNetPTPSyncInterval.description: The sync interval shall be the interval in seconds between successive Sync messages issued by master clocks. It shall have the same value for all clocks in a subdomain. The value of sync interval is a compromise between the inherent stability of the clocks, the responsiveness of the clocks in a subdomain to change, and the communication load imposed by PTP. Allowed values are 1,2,8,16 and 64. Changes are applied after the initialization with the init key init-with-nvm or after reboot if the configuration was saved.

hmNetPTPSubdomainName.name: hmNetPTPSubdomainName
hmNetPTPSubdomainName.description: Each subdomain shall be characterized by a name recognized by all PTP clocks in the subdomain as the basis for sending and receiving PTP communications. Changes are applied after the initialization with the init key init-with-nvm or afer reboot if the configuration was saved. The values of the octets for the subdomain name may be chosen from the set consisting of the values of the printable ASCII characters starting with hex value 0x21 (!) up to and including hex value 0x7E (~).

hmNetPTPOffsetFromMasterNanoSecs.name: hmNetPTPOffsetFromMasterNanoSecs
hmNetPTPOffsetFromMasterNanoSecs.description: Current offset between its parent and this node in nanoseconds. Values greater than 1 second or less than -1 second are indicated by the maximum or minimum INTEGER values.

hmNetPTPAbsMaxOffset.name: hmNetPTPAbsMaxOffset
hmNetPTPAbsMaxOffset.description: This members value shall indicate the absolute value for the maximum offset between its parent and this node. The value is set to zero if the offset is the first time smaller than hmNetPTPSyncLowerBound. Offsets bigger than +/-1 second is indicated by the maximum value

hmNetPTPOneWayDelayNanoSecs.name: hmNetPTPOneWayDelayNanoSecs
hmNetPTPOneWayDelayNanoSecs.description: Current one_way_delay between its parent and this node in nanoseconds. Values greater than 1 second or less than -1 second are indicated by the maximum or minimum INTEGER values.

hmNetPTPTimeSeconds.name: hmNetPTPTimeSeconds
hmNetPTPTimeSeconds.description: This members value shall indicate PTP time in seconds since 1.1.1970.

hmNetPTPObservedDrift.name: hmNetPTPObservedDrift
hmNetPTPObservedDrift.description: Relative rate (frequency or drift) between its parent and this node in nanoseconds. Values greater than 1 second or less than -1 second are indicated by the maximum or minimum INTEGER values.

hmNetPTPPiIntegral.name: hmNetPTPPiIntegral
hmNetPTPPiIntegral.description: A digital PI servo has the following difference equation y(k) = y(k-1) + (Kp + Ki* T )* x(k) + Kp * x(k-1). This object specifies the Ki* 100000 term (integral part). Kp is 0.5. The default value of this object is 6250 that is Ki=1/16.

hmNetPTPParentUUID.name: hmNetPTPParentUUID
hmNetPTPParentUUID.description: The UUID of its Parent. For Ethernet this is the MAC address of the management agent.

hmNetPTPGrandmasterUUID.name: hmNetPTPGrandmasterUUID
hmNetPTPGrandmasterUUID.description: The UUID of its Grandmaster. For Ethernet this is the MAC address of the management agent.

hmNetPTPCurrentUTCOffset.name: hmNetPTPCurrentUTCOffset
hmNetPTPCurrentUTCOffset.description: UTC time differs from the TAI time by a constant offset. This offset is modified on occasion by adding or subtracting leap seconds. The current number of leap seconds is represented in PTP by the value of hmNetPTPCurrentUTCOffset.

hmNetPTPleap59.name: hmNetPTPleap59
hmNetPTPleap59.description: When TRUE the last minute of the current day will contain 59 seconds.

hmNetPTPleap61.name: hmNetPTPleap61
hmNetPTPleap61.description: When TRUE the last minute of the current day will contain 61 seconds.

hmNetPTPStepsRemoved.name: hmNetPTPStepsRemoved
hmNetPTPStepsRemoved.description: This members value shall be the number of communication paths traversed between the local clock and the grandmaster clock. For example, steps_removed in a slave clock on the same PTP communication path as the grandmaster clock will have a value of 1, indicating that a single path was traversed.

hmNetPTPEpochNumber.name: hmNetPTPEpochNumber
hmNetPTPEpochNumber.description: The PTP epoch began at 0 hours on 1 January 1970. Times measured since this epoch are designated in this standard as PTP Seconds. When the epoch is the PTP epoch, the value of the epoch number shall be the current number of times the 32-bit seconds clock has rolled over since the PTP epoch.

hmNetPTPStaticDrift.name: hmNetPTPStaticDrift
hmNetPTPStaticDrift.description: Relative rate (frequency or drift) between a reference clock and this node in nanoseconds per second (ns/s). This value is only applied if no port is in slave state.

hmNetPTPPortTable.name: hmNetPTPPortTable
hmNetPTPPortTable.description: This table contains variables for each PTP port of the switch.

hmNetPTPPortID.name: hmNetPTPPortID
hmNetPTPPortID.description: Index to identify a port of the switch unit. This value is never greater than hmSysGroupCapacity.

hmNetPTPPortState.name: hmNetPTPPortState
hmNetPTPPortState.description: State of the PTP port intance.

hmNetPTPPortEnable.name: hmNetPTPPortEnable
hmNetPTPPortEnable.description: The respective PTP Port of the Boundary Clock can be set to true (enabled) or set to false (disabled). If the port is disabled no PTP packets will be processed for the respective port.

hmNetPTP2PortTable.name: hmNetPTP2PortTable
hmNetPTP2PortTable.description: This table contains variables for each PTP2 port of the switch.

hmNetPTP2PortState.name: hmNetPTP2PortState
hmNetPTP2PortState.description: State of the PTP2 port intance.

hmNetPTP2PortCapability.name: hmNetPTP2PortCapability
hmNetPTP2PortCapability.description: This object shows the capability of the ptp port.

hmNetPTP2VlanID.name: hmNetPTP2VlanID
hmNetPTP2VlanID.description: VLAN in which PTP packets are send. With a value of -1 all packets are send untagged

hmNetPTP2VlanPriority.name: hmNetPTP2VlanPriority
hmNetPTP2VlanPriority.description: VLAN priority of tagged ptp packets

hmNetPTP2TCSyncLocalClock.name: hmNetPTP2TCSyncLocalClock
hmNetPTP2TCSyncLocalClock.description: Enable synchronisation of the local clock. This is only valid if syntonization is enabled

hmNetPTP2TCVlanID.name: hmNetPTP2TCVlanID
hmNetPTP2TCVlanID.description: VLAN in which PTP packets are send. With a value of -1 all packets are send untagged

hmNetPTP2TCVlanPriority.name: hmNetPTP2TCVlanPriority
hmNetPTP2TCVlanPriority.description: VLAN priority of tagged ptp packets

hmNetPTP2TCPortTable.name: hmNetPTP2TCPortTable
hmNetPTP2TCPortTable.description: This table contains variables for each PTP2 TC port of the switch.

hmNetSNMPAccessStatus.name: hmNetSNMPAccessStatus
hmNetSNMPAccessStatus.description: Enables/disables the SNMP protocol access on this device. If only read access is allowed set this object to readOnly(3).

hmNetSNMPSynchronizeV1V3Status.name: hmNetSNMPSynchronizeV1V3Status
hmNetSNMPSynchronizeV1V3Status.description: Enables/disables the synchronization between the SNMPv1 community and the SNMPv3 password. If enabled the first read-write community in hmAuthCommTable is used for the SNMPv3 admin password. This is the same password that is used in the user- and webinterface. Further, if enabled the first read-only community in hmAuthCommTable is used for the SNMPv3 user password.

hmNetSNMPPortNumber.name: hmNetSNMPPortNumber
hmNetSNMPPortNumber.description: The port number of the snmp server. To activate the port number the device has to be restarted.

hmNetSNMPRadiusAuthenticate.name: hmNetSNMPRadiusAuthenticate
hmNetSNMPRadiusAuthenticate.description: Enables/disables authentication of SNMPv3 users via RADIUS server

hmNetSNMPv3EncryptionReadWriteStatus.name: hmNetSNMPv3EncryptionReadWriteStatus
hmNetSNMPv3EncryptionReadWriteStatus.description: Enables/disables the SNMPv3 admin Data Encryption.

hmNetSNMPv3EncryptionReadOnlyStatus.name: hmNetSNMPv3EncryptionReadOnlyStatus
hmNetSNMPv3EncryptionReadOnlyStatus.description: Enables/disables the SNMPv3 user Data Encryption.

hmNetGPSIsAvailable.name: hmNetGPSIsAvailable
hmNetGPSIsAvailable.description: Indicates if a GPS module is available.

hmNetGPSIsSynchronized.name: hmNetGPSIsSynchronized
hmNetGPSIsSynchronized.description: Indicates if the GPS module is synchronized to the GPS signal.

hmNetGPSMode.name: hmNetGPSMode
hmNetGPSMode.description: Shows the mode of the GPS module. If hmNetGPSMode is gpsIn(1), the GPS module reads the signal from a GPS receiver in the format given in hmNetGPSTimeStringFormat. If the mode is gpsOut(2), the GPS module sends out a signal in the format given in hmNetGPSTimeStringFormat.

hmNetGPSTimeStringFormat.name: hmNetGPSTimeStringFormat
hmNetGPSTimeStringFormat.description: These are the GPS time string formats which a GPS module can read or write.

hmRMATable.name: hmRMATable
hmRMATable.description: A list of Management Access Entries (Rules) to increase security

hmRMAEntry.name: hmRMAEntry
hmRMAEntry.description: An entry contains a rule for the Management Access.

hmRMAIndex.name: hmRMAIndex
hmRMAIndex.description: The unique index used for each row in the RMA Table

hmRMARowStatus.name: hmRMARowStatus
hmRMARowStatus.description: Describes the status of a row in this table if it is active or not available ...

hmFSUpdFileName.name: hmFSUpdFileName
hmFSUpdFileName.description: Full specified filename of the update file e.g. tftp://192.9.200.1/upd/bootrom.v3 .

hmFSConfFileName.name: hmFSConfFileName
hmFSConfFileName.description: Full specified name of the configuration file e.g. tftp://192.9.200.1/cfg/config1.sav .

hmFSLogFileName.name: hmFSLogFileName
hmFSLogFileName.description: Local or full specified url of the log file. If value is local, the log will be written to the flash. e.g. tftp://192.9.200.1/log/log300599.log or local.

hmFSUserName.name: hmFSUserName
hmFSUserName.description: login name for the used file transport protocol.

hmFSTPPassword.name: hmFSTPPassword
hmFSTPPassword.description: password for the used file transport protocol.

hmFSAction.name: hmFSAction
hmFSAction.description: This object, when read, always returns a value of other (1). When set to update (2), the updatefile specified by hmFSUpdFileName will be loaded. config-load (3) will load the configuration stored in the local flash. config-save (4) will write the present configuration to the flash. config-load-remote (5) will load the configuration stored in a file specified by hmFSConfigFileName (which may be in binary or script format). config-save-remote (6) will save the present configuration in a file specified by hmFSConfigFileName. log-save (7) will save the local logfile to a file specified with hmFSLogFileName. config-load-default (8) will restore the default settings and set-to-factory (9) will apply the factory settings to the system and save the configuration to flash. log-clear (10) will clear the logfile of the agent. gbl-update (12) will perform a software update of the whole chassis. config-load-backup (13) loads an automatically saved backup configuration config-remote-and-save (15) loads a configuration via tftp and saves it to the flash. toggleImage (20) switches between main and backup software image to be active (so it will be loaded after the next coldstart). config-save-remote-script (21) saves the current configuration in script format to the file specified by hmFSConfigFileName. Any other value results in a badValue status code.

hmFSActionResult.name: hmFSActionResult
hmFSActionResult.description: Result of the last activated action.

hmFSBootConfiguration.name: hmFSBootConfiguration
hmFSBootConfiguration.description: By setting this MIB variable the user can control which configuration should be read during system initialization: default(1) : boot with factory settings local(2) : boot with locally stored configuration

hmFSRunningConfiguration.name: hmFSRunningConfiguration
hmFSRunningConfiguration.description: By setting this MIB variable the user can control which configuration should be read after switch initialization: boot(1) : the one which is selected by hmFSBootConfiguration local(2) : boot with locally stored configuration remote(3) : use the remotely stored configuration according to hmFSConfFileName

hmFSLastMessage.name: hmFSLastMessage
hmFSLastMessage.description: error message of the last hmFSAction performed. If there was no error encountered, the value of this variable will be 'OK'

hmConfigurationStatus.name: hmConfigurationStatus
hmConfigurationStatus.description: Status of the local configuration. ok(1): Local and running configuration match. notInSync(2): Local and running configuration don't match, configuration has not yet been saved.

hmFSFileTable.name: hmFSFileTable
hmFSFileTable.description: a directory of the internal file system

hmFSFileID.name: hmFSFileID
hmFSFileID.description: This index is used to identify the associated file

hmFSFileDate.name: hmFSFileDate
hmFSFileDate.description: date in UNIX format (seconds since 1 jan 1970)

hmAutoconfigAdapterStatus.name: hmAutoconfigAdapterStatus
hmAutoconfigAdapterStatus.description: Status of the AutoConfiguration Adapter. notPresent(1): AutoConfiguration Adapter has not been detected. removed(2): Configuration was loaded from adapter, but adapter was removed in running mode of the agent. ok(3): Configuration of adapter and switch match. notInSync(4): Configuration of adapter and switch don't match, e.g. configuration has not yet been written into the adapter. outOfMemory(5): Configuration is too large for the adapter. wrongMachine(6): Adapter contains configuration which cannot be loaded into this machine because it was created by a different type of switch. checksumErr(7): Data in adapter fails consistency check. genericErr(8): Any other failure, e.g. hardware malfunction. autodisabled(9): USB port has been disabled for safety reasons.

hmAutoconfigAdapterSerialNum.name: hmAutoconfigAdapterSerialNum
hmAutoconfigAdapterSerialNum.description: The serial number provided by vendor (ASCII).

hmConfigWatchdogAdminStatus.name: hmConfigWatchdogAdminStatus
hmConfigWatchdogAdminStatus.description: Administrative status of the configuration watchdog. enable(1): start/trigger the watchdog timer disable(2): turn off the watchdog This feature provides recovery from situations where the switch cannot be reached by the management station anymore. Whenever this variable is set to enable(1), the value of hmConfigWatchdogTimeInterval is loaded into the watchdog timer. This timer must be triggered before hmConfigWatchdogTimerValue reaches 0. If the watchdog timer expires, the last saved configuration of the switch will be restored. The watchdog is triggered with MIB read and write accesses

hmConfigWatchdogOperStatus.name: hmConfigWatchdogOperStatus
hmConfigWatchdogOperStatus.description: Operational status of the configuration watchdog. enable(1): watchdog up and running disable(2): watchdog inactive

hmConfigWatchdogTimeInterval.name: hmConfigWatchdogTimeInterval
hmConfigWatchdogTimeInterval.description: Period of the watchdog timer in seconds.

hmConfigWatchdogTimerValue.name: hmConfigWatchdogTimerValue
hmConfigWatchdogTimerValue.description: Current count-down value of the watchdog timer in seconds.

hmConfigWatchdogIPAddress.name: hmConfigWatchdogIPAddress
hmConfigWatchdogIPAddress.description: Current IP Adress of station that triggers the watchdog.

hmTemperature.name: hmTemperature
hmTemperature.description: This signed integer is used to identify the temperature within the agent in units of centigrade (celsius).

hmTempUprLimit.name: hmTempUprLimit
hmTempUprLimit.description: This value is used to define a maximum level for the temperature within an agent. If the temperature rises above this upper limit, the management station will be notified by a hmTemperature trap.

hmTempLwrLimit.name: hmTempLwrLimit
hmTempLwrLimit.description: This value is used to define a minimum level for the temperature within a concentrator. If the temperature falls below this lower limit, the management station will be notified by a hmTemperature trap.

hmNeighbourAgentTable.name: hmNeighbourAgentTable
hmNeighbourAgentTable.description: A list of the neighbour agents in a chassis

hmNeighbourSlot.name: hmNeighbourSlot
hmNeighbourSlot.description: An index that uniquely identifies an agent by the slot in the chassis.

hmNeighbourIpAddress.name: hmNeighbourIpAddress
hmNeighbourIpAddress.description: The IP Address of the agent.

hmAuthHostTableEntriesMax.name: hmAuthHostTableEntriesMax
hmAuthHostTableEntriesMax.description: The maximum possible number of entries in the hmAuthHostTable. This value equates to the total number of trusted Hosts which potentially may be recognized.

hmAuthCommTableEntriesMax.name: hmAuthCommTableEntriesMax
hmAuthCommTableEntriesMax.description: The maximum possible number of entries in the hmAuthCommTable. This value equates to the total number of communities which ly may be recognized.

hmAuthCommTable.name: hmAuthCommTable
hmAuthCommTable.description: A list of valid SNMP Community Entries.

hmAuthCommEntry.name: hmAuthCommEntry
hmAuthCommEntry.description: A list of SNMP Community properties.

hmAuthCommIndex.name: hmAuthCommIndex
hmAuthCommIndex.description: An index that uniquely identifies an ordered entry in the SNMP Community Table.

hmAuthCommName.name: hmAuthCommName
hmAuthCommName.description: The name of this SNMP Community Entry, e.g. public. This object can only be written.

hmAuthCommPerm.name: hmAuthCommPerm
hmAuthCommPerm.description: The Read/Write (GET/SET) permission for the community. A (1) indicates perm-ro (GET) permission. A (2) indicates perm-wr (GET/SET) permission.

hmAuthCommState.name: hmAuthCommState
hmAuthCommState.description: The state of this community entry. Enable (1) defines an entry that is valid. Disable (2) defines an entry that is valid but not enabled. Delete (3) removes an entry from the table. Invalid (4) defines an entry that is no longer valid (e.g., an entry that was deleted) and should be ignored. An attempt to set a value of invalid (4) causes the agent to return SNMP_BADVALUE.

hmAuthHostTable.name: hmAuthHostTable
hmAuthHostTable.description: A list of valid SNMP Trusted Host Entries.

hmAuthHostEntry.name: hmAuthHostEntry
hmAuthHostEntry.description: A list of SNMP Host properties.

hmAuthHostIndex.name: hmAuthHostIndex
hmAuthHostIndex.description: An index that uniquely identifies an ordered entry in the SNMP Trusted Host Table.

hmAuthHostName.name: hmAuthHostName
hmAuthHostName.description: The name of this SNMP Trusted Host Entry, e.g. host1.

hmAuthHostCommIndex.name: hmAuthHostCommIndex
hmAuthHostCommIndex.description: The index of this SNMP Trusted Host Entry's community entry in the hmAuthCommTable.

hmAuthHostIpAddress.name: hmAuthHostIpAddress
hmAuthHostIpAddress.description: The IP Address for the host. This identified host has permission to access information in this device's MIB tables, providing the SNMP security toggle is on (see hmMiscSNMPSecurity).

hmAuthHostIpMask.name: hmAuthHostIpMask
hmAuthHostIpMask.description: The Network Mask for the trusted Host entry.

hmAuthHostState.name: hmAuthHostState
hmAuthHostState.description: The state of this trusted host entry. Enable (1) defines an entry that is valid. Disable (2) defines an entry that is valid but not enabled. Delete (3) removes an entry from the table. Invalid (4) defines an entry that is no longer valid (e.g., an entry that was deleted) and should be ignored. An attempt to set a value of invalid (4) causes the agent to return SNMP_BADVALUE.

hmTrapCommTableEntriesMax.name: hmTrapCommTableEntriesMax
hmTrapCommTableEntriesMax.description: The total number of entries in the hmTrapCommTable. This value equates to the total number of communities which potentially can be recognized.

hmTrapDestTableEntriesMax.name: hmTrapDestTableEntriesMax
hmTrapDestTableEntriesMax.description: The total number of entries in the hmTrapDestTable. This equates to the total number of hosts which can potentially be sent SNMP traps.

hmTrapCommTable.name: hmTrapCommTable
hmTrapCommTable.description: A list of valid SNMP Community Entries used for Traps.

hmTrapCommEntry.name: hmTrapCommEntry
hmTrapCommEntry.description: A list of SNMP Trap Community properties.

hmTrapCommIndex.name: hmTrapCommIndex
hmTrapCommIndex.description: An index that uniquely identifies an ordered entry in the SNMP Community Trap Table.

hmTrapCommCommIndex.name: hmTrapCommCommIndex
hmTrapCommCommIndex.description: The communities entry index of this SNMP Trap Community Entry.

hmTrapCommColdStart.name: hmTrapCommColdStart
hmTrapCommColdStart.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP ColdStart Trap for this SNMP community.

hmTrapCommLinkDown.name: hmTrapCommLinkDown
hmTrapCommLinkDown.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Link Down traps for this SNMP community.

hmTrapCommLinkUp.name: hmTrapCommLinkUp
hmTrapCommLinkUp.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Link Up traps for this SNMP community.

hmTrapCommAuthentication.name: hmTrapCommAuthentication
hmTrapCommAuthentication.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Authentication traps for this SNMP community.

hmTrapCommBridge.name: hmTrapCommBridge
hmTrapCommBridge.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Bridge MIB traps for this SNMP community. Available Traps: newRoot (MACH) topologyChange (MACH)

hmTrapCommRMON.name: hmTrapCommRMON
hmTrapCommRMON.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP RMON traps for this SNMP community. Available Traps: risingAlarm (MACH, MICE, RS2) fallingAlarm (MACH, MICE, RS2)

hmTrapCommUsergroup.name: hmTrapCommUsergroup
hmTrapCommUsergroup.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Enterprise usergroup traps for this SNMP community. Available Traps: hmNewUserTrap (MACH) hmPortSecurityTrap (MACH, MICE, RS2) hmPortSecConfigErrorTrap (MACH)

hmTrapCommDualHoming.name: hmTrapCommDualHoming
hmTrapCommDualHoming.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Enterprise dual homing traps for this SNMP community. Available Traps: hmDuHmReconfig (MACH) hmDuHmRedundancy (MACH) hmRingRedReconfig (MACH, MICE)

hmTrapCommChassis.name: hmTrapCommChassis
hmTrapCommChassis.description: Enable (1) or Disable (2) the SNMP Enterprise chassis traps for this SNMP community. Available Traps: hmGroupMapChange (MACH) hmPowerSupply (MACH, MICE, RS2) hmFan (MACH) hmSignallingRelay (MICE, RS2) hmStandby (MACH, MICE, RS2) hmSelfTestError (MACH) hmModuleMapChange (MICE) hmTemperature (MACH) hmLoginTrap (MACH) hmDuplicateStaticAddressTrap (MACH)

hmTrapCommState.name: hmTrapCommState
hmTrapCommState.description: The state of this community entry. Enable (1) defines an entry that is valid. Disable (2) defines an entry that is valid but not enabled. Delete (3) removes an entry from the table. Invalid (4) defines an entry that is no longer valid (e.g., an entry that was deleted) and should be ignored. An attempt to set a value of invalid (4) causes the agent to return SNMP_BADVALUE.

hmTrapDestTable.name: hmTrapDestTable
hmTrapDestTable.description: A list of valid SNMP Trap Trusted Host Destination entries.

hmTrapDestEntry.name: hmTrapDestEntry
hmTrapDestEntry.description: A list of SNMP Trap Trusted Host Destination properties.

hmTrapDestIndex.name: hmTrapDestIndex
hmTrapDestIndex.description: An index that uniquely identifies an ordered entry in the SNMP Trusted Host Destination Table.

hmTrapDestName.name: hmTrapDestName
hmTrapDestName.description: The name of this SNMP Trusted Host Destination Entry, e.g. Admin.

hmTrapDestCommIndex.name: hmTrapDestCommIndex
hmTrapDestCommIndex.description: The communities entry index of this SNMP Trusted Host Destination Entry's community.

hmTrapDestIpAddress.name: hmTrapDestIpAddress
hmTrapDestIpAddress.description: The IP Address for the host. This identified host has permission to access information in this device's MIB tables, providing the SNMP security toggle is on (see hmMiscSNMPSecurity).

hmTrapDestIpMask.name: hmTrapDestIpMask
hmTrapDestIpMask.description: The Network Mask for the trusted Host Destination entry.

hmTrapDestState.name: hmTrapDestState
hmTrapDestState.description: The state of this trusted trap destination entry. Enable (1) defines an entry that is valid. Disable (2) defines an entry that is valid but not enabled. Delete (3) removes an entry from the table. Invalid (4) defines an entry that is no longer valid (e.g., an entry that was deleted) and should be ignored. An attempt to set a value of invalid (4) causes the agent to return SNMP_BADVALUE.

hmLastIpAddr.name: hmLastIpAddr
hmLastIpAddr.description: IP Address specified in the last request.

hmLastPort.name: hmLastPort
hmLastPort.description: UDP port specified in the last request.

hmIGMPSnoopStatus.name: hmIGMPSnoopStatus
hmIGMPSnoopStatus.description: Enables/disables IGMP Snooping on this device. The default value is disable.

hmIGMPSnoopAgingTime.name: hmIGMPSnoopAgingTime
hmIGMPSnoopAgingTime.description: The timeout period in seconds for aging out Multicast Groups dynamically learned with IGMP Snooping. Note that aging operates on a per interface per multicast group basis. This interval is also used to age out ports that have received IGMP Router Query PDUs. The default is 260 seconds and the range is 3 to 3600 seconds.

hmIGMPSnoopUnknownMode.name: hmIGMPSnoopUnknownMode
hmIGMPSnoopUnknownMode.description: Sets the mode how unknown Multicast packets will be treated. The default value is flood(2).

hmIGMPSnoopUnknownAgingTime.name: hmIGMPSnoopUnknownAgingTime
hmIGMPSnoopUnknownAgingTime.description: The timeout period in seconds approximately for aging out Unknown Multicast Groups dynamically learned with traffic snooping. The exactly value is UnknownLookupInterval/(UnknownLookupInterval-UnknownLookupResponseTime)*UnknownAgingTime. Note that aging operates on a per unknown multicast group basis. The default is 260 seconds and the range is 3 to 3600 seconds.

hmIGMPSnoopUnknownLookupInterval.name: hmIGMPSnoopUnknownLookupInterval
hmIGMPSnoopUnknownLookupInterval.description: The frequency at which Unknown Multicast Groups dynamically learned with traffic snooping are traffic checked by the switch in seconds. So this is the time between periodic traffic checking in which unknown multicast groups being aged on the switch when it is acting as Trafficsnooper. Large values lead to traffic checking less often. The default is 125 seconds and the range is 2 to 3599 seconds.

hmIGMPSnoopUnknownLookupResponseTime.name: hmIGMPSnoopUnknownLookupResponseTime
hmIGMPSnoopUnknownLookupResponseTime.description: The unknown lookup response time in seconds in which Unknown Multicast Groups dynamically learned with traffic snooping are traffic checked. So this is the time in which response traffic to the Trafficsnooper allowing the update of unknown multicast group aging timer. This variable enables the checking of bursty unknown multicast traffic. Small values lead to bad traffic checking but few snooper load and large values lead to good traffic checking but more snooper load. The default is 10 seconds and the range is 1 to 3598 seconds.

hmIGMPSnoopQuerierToPortmask.name: hmIGMPSnoopQuerierToPortmask
hmIGMPSnoopQuerierToPortmask.description: Enables or disables the addition of query ports to multicast filter portmasks.

hmIGMPSnoopQuerierIPAddress.name: hmIGMPSnoopQuerierIPAddress
hmIGMPSnoopQuerierIPAddress.description: Shows the IP address of the active querier.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryTable.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryTable
hmIGMPSnoopQueryTable.description: A table displaying the IGMP Router Query PDU ports.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryEntry.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryEntry
hmIGMPSnoopQueryEntry.description: A table displaying the IGMP Router Query PDU ports. These are maintained on a per VLAN basis.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryVlanIndex.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryVlanIndex
hmIGMPSnoopQueryVlanIndex.description: This is the VLAN index for which this entry is valid. If the switch only supports shared vlan learning (SVL), the value is always 1 and there is only 1 instance in the table.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryPorts.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryPorts
hmIGMPSnoopQueryPorts.description: This read-only object displays the set of ports that have received IGMP Router Query PDUs for this VLAN as determined by the IGMP Snooping task.

hmIGMPSnoopFilterTable.name: hmIGMPSnoopFilterTable
hmIGMPSnoopFilterTable.description: A table containing the multicast filtering information on a per vlan basis learned with IGMP Snooping.

hmIGMPSnoopFilterVlanIndex.name: hmIGMPSnoopFilterVlanIndex
hmIGMPSnoopFilterVlanIndex.description: This is the VLAN index for which this entry is valid. If the switch only supports shared vlan learning (SVL), the value is always 1 and there is only 1 instance in the table.

hmIGMPSnoopFilterAddress.name: hmIGMPSnoopFilterAddress
hmIGMPSnoopFilterAddress.description: The multicast destination MAC address in a frame to which this entry's filtering information applies.

hmIGMPSnoopFilterLearntPorts.name: hmIGMPSnoopFilterLearntPorts
hmIGMPSnoopFilterLearntPorts.description: The set of ports, to which frames destined for this Group MAC Address learned by IGMP Snooping are currently being forwarded. Each octet within the value of this object specifies a set of eight ports, with the first octet specifying ports 1 through 8, the second octet specifying ports 9 through 16, etc. Within each octet, the most significant bit represents the lowest numbered port, and the least significant bit represents the highest numbered port. Thus, each port of the bridge is represented by a single bit within the value of this object. If that bit has a value of '1' then that port is included in the set of ports; the port is not included if its bit has a value of '0'. (Note that the setting of the bit corresponding to the port from which a frame is received is irrelevant.)

hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllTable.name: hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllTable
hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllTable.description: A table containing forwarding information for each VLAN, specifying the set of ports to which forwarding of all multicasts applies, configured statically by management. An entry appears in this table for all VLANs that are currently instantiated.

hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllEntry.name: hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllEntry
hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllEntry.description: Forwarding information for a VLAN, specifying the set of ports to which all multicasts should be forwarded, configured statically by management.

hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllVlanIndex.name: hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllVlanIndex
hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllVlanIndex.description: This is the VLAN index for which this entry is valid. If the switch only supports shared vlan learning (SVL), the value is always 1 and there is only 1 instance in the table.

hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllStaticPorts.name: hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllStaticPorts
hmIGMPSnoopForwardAllStaticPorts.description: The set of ports configured by management in this VLAN to which all multicast group-addressed frames learned by IGMP are to be forwarded. This value will be restored after the device is reset.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticTable.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticTable
hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticTable.description: A table displaying the IGMP Static Query ports.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticVlanIndex.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticVlanIndex
hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticVlanIndex.description: This is the VLAN index for which this entry is valid. If the switch only supports shared vlan learning (SVL), the value is always 1 and there is only 1 instance in the table.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticPorts.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticPorts
hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticPorts.description: The set of ports explicitly configured by management to be IGMP-forwarding ports.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticAutomaticPorts.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticAutomaticPorts
hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticAutomaticPorts.description: The set of ports that are automatically learned by LLDP protocol to be IGMP-forwarding ports.

hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticAutomaticPortsEnab.name: hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticAutomaticPortsEnable
hmIGMPSnoopQueryStaticAutomaticPortsEnab.description: The set of ports that are allowed to be learned automatically by LLDP protocol to be IGMP-forwarding ports.

hmIGMPQuerierStatus.name: hmIGMPQuerierStatus
hmIGMPQuerierStatus.description: Enables/disables IGMP Querier on this device. IGMP queries are only sent when hmIGMPSnoopStatus is also set. The default value is disable.

hmIGMPQuerierMode.name: hmIGMPQuerierMode
hmIGMPQuerierMode.description: Shows the current mode of the IGMP Querier.

hmIGMPQuerierTransmitInterval.name: hmIGMPQuerierTransmitInterval
hmIGMPQuerierTransmitInterval.description: The frequency at which IGMP general query packets are transmitted by the querying switch in seconds. So this is the time between general periodic queries being sent out of the switch when it is acting as the IGMP querier. Large values lead to IGMP queries being sent less often. The default is 125 seconds and the range is 2 to 3599 seconds.

hmIGMPQuerierMaxResponseTime.name: hmIGMPQuerierMaxResponseTime
hmIGMPQuerierMaxResponseTime.description: The maximum query response time in seconds advertised in IGMP v2 queries on this VLAN if the switch is the querier. Smaller values allow a switch to prune groups faster. So it is the maximum response time inserted into the general periodic queries. This variable enables the tuning of the burstiness of the IGMP traffic. If it is increased the responses have a larger time span in which to be generated by the hosts. The default is 10 seconds and the range is 1 to 3598 seconds.

hmIGMPQuerierProtocolVersion.name: hmIGMPQuerierProtocolVersion
hmIGMPQuerierProtocolVersion.description: The Querier protocol version. The default is version 2.

hmGmrpUnknownMode.name: hmGmrpUnknownMode
hmGmrpUnknownMode.description: Sets the mode how unknown multicast packets will be treated. The default value is flood(2).

hmRelayOption82Status.name: hmRelayOption82Status
hmRelayOption82Status.description: Enables/disables the DHCP Option 82 defined in RFC 3046 on this device.

hmRelayOptionRemoteIDType.name: hmRelayOptionRemoteIDType
hmRelayOptionRemoteIDType.description: This option determines the content of the Agent Remote ID (sub-option 2). ip(1) inserts the ip address of the relay's mgmt-interface and encodes it with sub option type A1. mac(2) inserts the mac adress of the relay's mgmt-interface and encodes it with sub option type 00. client-id(3) inserts the client identifier (sysName) of the relay's mgmt-interface and encodes it with sub option type A2. other(4) inserts the value in hmRelayOptionRemoteIDValue and encodes it with sub option type A3.

hmRelayOptionRemoteID.name: hmRelayOptionRemoteID
hmRelayOptionRemoteID.description: Displays the actual content of the Remote ID sub option for this relay agent. The value is encoded in TLV (Type-Length-Value) format. The following type values are currently defined: 00 = mac adress A1 = ip address A2 = client identifier A3 = string in hmRelayOptionRemoteIDValue

hmRelayOptionRemoteIDValue.name: hmRelayOptionRemoteIDValue
hmRelayOptionRemoteIDValue.description: Contains an octet string to be used as value for Agent Remote ID Sub-option type A3

hmRelayDHCPServerIpAddr.name: hmRelayDHCPServerIpAddr
hmRelayDHCPServerIpAddr.description: The IP address of the first DHCP-server to be addressed by the relay agent. If 0.0.0.0, DHCP relaying is switched off for this entry.

hmRelayDHCPServer2IpAddr.name: hmRelayDHCPServer2IpAddr
hmRelayDHCPServer2IpAddr.description: The IP address of the second DHCP-server to be addressed by the relay agent. If 0.0.0.0, DHCP relaying is switched off for this entry.

hmRelayDHCPServer3IpAddr.name: hmRelayDHCPServer3IpAddr
hmRelayDHCPServer3IpAddr.description: The IP address of the third DHCP-server to be addressed by the relay agent. If 0.0.0.0, DHCP relaying is switched off for this entry.

hmRelayDHCPServer4IpAddr.name: hmRelayDHCPServer4IpAddr
hmRelayDHCPServer4IpAddr.description: The IP address of the fourth DHCP-server to be addressed by the relay agent. If 0.0.0.0, DHCP relaying is switched off for this entry.

hmRelayInterfaceTable.name: hmRelayInterfaceTable
hmRelayInterfaceTable.description: This table contains variables for each interface of the switch.

hmRelayIfaceGroupID.name: hmRelayIfaceGroupID
hmRelayIfaceGroupID.description: index to identify an interface card. This value is never greater than hmSysGroupCapacity.

hmRelayIfaceID.name: hmRelayIfaceID
hmRelayIfaceID.description: index to identify an interface within an interface card.

hmRelayIfaceOption82Enable.name: hmRelayIfaceOption82Enable
hmRelayIfaceOption82Enable.description: Enable or disable DHCP Option 82 on this physical port.

hmRelayIfaceBCRequestFwd.name: hmRelayIfaceBCRequestFwd
hmRelayIfaceBCRequestFwd.description: Enable or disable relaying of incoming broadcasted BOOTP/DHCP request packets on this physical port. Hirschmann Multicast BOOTP/DHCP requests will always be relayed.

hmRelayIfaceCircuitID.name: hmRelayIfaceCircuitID
hmRelayIfaceCircuitID.description: Contains the actual Circuit ID sub option for this interface of the relay agent. It is a best guess value, since some information is not known before the actual reception of a BOOTP/DHCP request message.

hmRelayBCPktInCnt.name: hmRelayBCPktInCnt
hmRelayBCPktInCnt.description: The number of BOOTP/DHCP broadcast request packets received by the relay agent.

hmRelayMCPktInCnt.name: hmRelayMCPktInCnt
hmRelayMCPktInCnt.description: The number of BOOTP/DHCP multicast request packets received by the relay agent.

hmRelayPktServerRelayCnt.name: hmRelayPktServerRelayCnt
hmRelayPktServerRelayCnt.description: The number of BOOTP/DHCP requests relayed to the DHCP Server.

hmRelayPktClientRelayCnt.name: hmRelayPktClientRelayCnt
hmRelayPktClientRelayCnt.description: The number of BOOTP/DHCP replies relayed to the Client.

hmRelayErrCnt.name: hmRelayErrCnt
hmRelayErrCnt.description: The number of errors encountered within the relay agent.

hmRelayLastDuplicateIP.name: hmRelayLastDuplicateIP
hmRelayLastDuplicateIP.description: The last duplicate ip address encounterd by the relay agent.

hmSigConConfigTable.name: hmSigConConfigTable
hmSigConConfigTable.description: This table contains all variables to configure the behaviour of the signalling contacts.

hmSigConID.name: hmSigConID
hmSigConID.description: This index is used to identify the associated signalling contact.

hmSigConTrapEnable.name: hmSigConTrapEnable
hmSigConTrapEnable.description: Determines wether a trap shall be sent or not, when the signal contact operating state changes.

hmSigConTrapCause.name: hmSigConTrapCause
hmSigConTrapCause.description: This object identifies the cause for a trap. The index of the entity which produces the trap is specified by hmSigConTrapCauseIndex.

hmSigConTrapCauseIndex.name: hmSigConTrapCauseIndex
hmSigConTrapCauseIndex.description: This attribute specifies the entity which produces the trap. 1 - n: index of powersupply table / interfaces table 0: other errors

hmSigConMode.name: hmSigConMode
hmSigConMode.description: This attribute specifies the behaviour of the relay contact. The factory settings for signal contact 1 is monitoring the correct operation of entries specified to be survied. When the device has also a second signal contact, the factory setting for it is the manual mode.

hmSigConManualActivate.name: hmSigConManualActivate
hmSigConManualActivate.description: When operating in manual mode, the signal contact state can be set by this attribute.

hmSigConOperState.name: hmSigConOperState
hmSigConOperState.description: This attribute shows the current operating state of the signal contact.

hmSigConSenseLinkFailure.name: hmSigConSenseLinkFailure
hmSigConSenseLinkFailure.description: Sets the monitoring of the network connection(s).

hmSigConSenseControlLine.name: hmSigConSenseControlLine
hmSigConSenseControlLine.description: Sets the monitoring of the ring/network coupling.

hmSigConSenseRedNotGuaranteed.name: hmSigConSenseRedNotGuaranteed
hmSigConSenseRedNotGuaranteed.description: Sets the monitoring of the HIPER-Ring.

hmSigConSensePS1State.name: hmSigConSensePS1State
hmSigConSensePS1State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 1.

hmSigConSensePS2State.name: hmSigConSensePS2State
hmSigConSensePS2State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 2.

hmSigConSenseTemperature.name: hmSigConSenseTemperature
hmSigConSenseTemperature.description: Sets the monitoring of the device temperature.

hmSigConSenseModuleRemoval.name: hmSigConSenseModuleRemoval
hmSigConSenseModuleRemoval.description: Sets the monitoring of module removal (platform dependant).

hmSigConSenseACARemoval.name: hmSigConSenseACARemoval
hmSigConSenseACARemoval.description: Sets the monitoring of the auto configuration adapter removal.

hmSigConSensePS3State.name: hmSigConSensePS3State
hmSigConSensePS3State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 3 (platform dependant).

hmSigConSensePS4State.name: hmSigConSensePS4State
hmSigConSensePS4State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 4 (platform dependant).

hmSigConSenseFan1State.name: hmSigConSenseFan1State
hmSigConSenseFan1State.description: Sets the monitoring of the cooling fan (platform dependant).

hmSigConSensePS5State.name: hmSigConSensePS5State
hmSigConSensePS5State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 5 (platform dependant).

hmSigConSensePS6State.name: hmSigConSensePS6State
hmSigConSensePS6State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 6 (platform dependant).

hmSigConSensePS7State.name: hmSigConSensePS7State
hmSigConSensePS7State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 7 (platform dependant).

hmSigConSensePS8State.name: hmSigConSensePS8State
hmSigConSensePS8State.description: Sets the monitoring of the power supply 8 (platform dependant).

hmSigConSenseACANotInSync.name: hmSigConSenseACANotInSync
hmSigConSenseACANotInSync.description: Sets the monitoring whether the configuration on ACA is in sync with the configuration in NVRAM.

hmSigConLinkTable.name: hmSigConLinkTable
hmSigConLinkTable.description: This table contains all variables to mask an alarm for the signalling relay, produced by a link. The index for a link corresponds with ifMauIfIndex. The table is also used for the device monitoring configuration.

hmSigConLinkID.name: hmSigConLinkID
hmSigConLinkID.description: This index is used to identify the associated link and corresponds with ifMauIfIndex.

hmSigConLinkAlarm.name: hmSigConLinkAlarm
hmSigConLinkAlarm.description: Indicates whether an alarm for the signalling relay of the associated link will be produced or not, so you can mask the value of ifMauMediaAvailable.

hmDevMonConfigTable.name: hmDevMonConfigTable
hmDevMonConfigTable.description: This table contains all variables to configure the behaviour of the device state.

hmDevMonID.name: hmDevMonID
hmDevMonID.description: This index is used to identify the associated device status (currently only one).

hmDevMonTrapEnable.name: hmDevMonTrapEnable
hmDevMonTrapEnable.description: Determines wether a trap shall be sent or not, when the device monitoring state changes.

hmDevMonTrapCause.name: hmDevMonTrapCause
hmDevMonTrapCause.description: This object identifies the cause for a trap. The index of the entity which produces the trap is specified by hmDevMonTrapCauseIndex.

hmDevMonTrapCauseIndex.name: hmDevMonTrapCauseIndex
hmDevMonTrapCauseIndex.description: This attribute specifies the entity which produces the trap. 1 - n: index of powersupply table / interfaces table 0: other errors

hmDevMonSwitchState.name: hmDevMonSwitchState
hmDevMonSwitchState.description: This attribute shows the current state of the device monitoring.

hmDevMonSenseLinkFailure.name: hmDevMonSenseLinkFailure

hmAgentSnmpCommunityCreate.description: Creates a new SNMP Community entry. Defaults: IPAddress 0.0.0.0 IpMask 0.0.0.0 AccessMode read-only Status config

hmAgentSnmpCommunityConfigTable.name: hmAgentSnmpCommunityConfigTable
hmAgentSnmpCommunityConfigTable.description: A table of the switch's SNMP Config entries

hmAgentSnmpCommunityName.name: hmAgentSnmpCommunityName
hmAgentSnmpCommunityName.description: The switch's Snmp Community Name This name identifies each SNMP community; the name can be up to 32 characters, and it is case-sensitive. Community names in the SNMP community must be unique. If you make multiple entries using the same community name, the first entry is kept and processed and all duplicate entries are ignored.

hmAgentSnmpCommunityIPAddress.name: hmAgentSnmpCommunityIPAddress
hmAgentSnmpCommunityIPAddress.description: The switch's Snmp Community IP Address Client IP Address - This attribute is an IP address (or portion thereof) from which this device will accept SNMP packets with the associated community. The requesting entity's IP address is logical-ANDed with the Client IP Mask and the result must match the Client IP Address. Note: If the Client IP Mask is set to 0.0.0.0, a Client IP Address of 0.0.0.0 matches all IP addresses.

hmAgentSnmpCommunityIPMask.name: hmAgentSnmpCommunityIPMask
hmAgentSnmpCommunityIPMask.description: The switch's Snmp Community IP Mask Client IP Mask - This attribute is a mask to be logical-ANDed with the requesting entity's IP address before comparison with the Client IP Address. If the result matches with Client IP Address then the address is an authenticated IP address. For example, if the Client IP Address is 9.47.128.0 and the corresponding Client IP Mask is 255.255.255.0, a range of incoming IP addresses would match, that is, the incoming IP addresses could be a value in the following range: 9.47.128.0 to 9.47.128.255. To have a specific IP address be the only authenticated IP address, set the Client IP Address to the required IP address and set the Client IP Mask to 255.255.255.255.

hmAgentSnmpCommunityAccessMode.name: hmAgentSnmpCommunityAccessMode
hmAgentSnmpCommunityAccessMode.description: The switch's Snmp Community Access Mode Access Mode - This value can be read-only or read/write. A community with a read-only access allows for switch information to be displayed. A community with a read/write access allows for configuration changes to be made and for information to be displayed.

hmAgentSnmpCommunityStatus.name: hmAgentSnmpCommunityStatus
hmAgentSnmpCommunityStatus.description: The switch's Snmp Community Status. active(1) - This community is active, allowing SNMP managers associated with this community to manage the switch according to its access right. notInService(2) - This community is not active; no SNMP requests using this community will be accepted. In this case the SNMP manager associated with this community cannot manage the switch until the Status is changed back to active(1). config(3) - The community Status must be set to this value in order to configure it. When creating a new community entry, initial Status will be set to this value. destroy(4) - Set to this value to remove the community from the agent.

hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigTable.name: hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigTable
hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigTable.description: Trap messages are sent across a network to an SNMP Network Manager. These messages alert the manager to events occurring within the switch or on the network. Up to six simultaneous trap receivers are supported.

hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigEntry.name: hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverConfigEntry

hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverCommunityName.name: hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverCommunityName

hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress.name: hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress
hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress.description: IP Address - Each IP address parameter is four integer numbers. The numbers range from 0 to 255.

hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverStatus.name: hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverStatus
hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverStatus.description: The switch's Snmp Trap Reciever Status. active(1) - This trap receiver is active, allowing SNMP Traps to be sent to this receiver. notInService(2) - This trap reciever is not active; no SNMP Traps will be sent to this reciever until it's set back to active(1). config(3) - The trap reciever Status must be set to this value in order to configure it. When creating a new trap receiver entry, the Status will initially be set to this value. Note: hmAgentSnmpTrapReceiverIPAddress must be set to non-zero before changing to active(1) or notInService(2). destroy(4) - Set to this value to remove the trap receiver entry from the agent.

hmAgentSnmpLinkUpDownTrapFlag.name: hmAgentSnmpLinkUpDownTrapFlag
hmAgentSnmpLinkUpDownTrapFlag.description: Link Up/Down Flag - Enable/Disable Link Up/Link Down traps for the entire switch. When set to Enable, the Link Up/Down traps will be sent only if the Link Trap flag setting associated with the port (Port Configuration Menu) is set to Enable.

hmAgentSnmpMultipleUsersTrapFlag.name: hmAgentSnmpMultipleUsersTrapFlag
hmAgentSnmpMultipleUsersTrapFlag.description: Multiple Users Flag - Enable/Disable Multiple User traps. When the value is set to Enable, a Multiple User Trap is sent whenever someone logs in to the terminal interface (EIA 232 or Telnet) and there is already an existing terminal interface session.

hmAgentSnmpSpanningTreeTrapFlag.name: hmAgentSnmpSpanningTreeTrapFlag
hmAgentSnmpSpanningTreeTrapFlag.description: Spanning Tree Flag - This flag enables the sending of new root traps and topology change notification traps.

hmAgentSnmpBroadcastStormTrapFlag.name: hmAgentSnmpBroadcastStormTrapFlag
hmAgentSnmpBroadcastStormTrapFlag.description: Broadcast Storm Flag - This flag enables or disables the broadcast storm trap. You must also enable Broadcast Storm Recovery Mode (see the Switch Configuration Menu). When this value is set to Enable and Broadcast Storm Recovery mode is set to Enable, the Broadcast Storm Start/End traps are sent when the switch enters and leaves Broadcast Storm Recovery.

hmPowerSupply.name: hmPowerSupply
hmPowerSupply.description: This trap is sent if the state of a power supply unit changes.

hmFan.name: hmFan
hmFan.description: This trap is sent if the value of hmFanCtrl changes.

hmStandby.name: hmStandby

hmSelftestError.name: hmSelftestError

hmSigConRelayChange.name: hmSigConRelayChange

hmSFPChangeTrap.name: hmSFPChangeTrap
hmSFPChangeTrap.description: This trap is sent when a SFP has been added or removed. It is also sent for an otherwise unsupported SFP.

hmIfaceUtilizationTrap.name: hmIfaceUtilizationTrap
hmIfaceUtilizationTrap.description: This trap is sent if the value of hmIfaceUtilization exceeds or falls back below the interface untilization threshholds hmIfaceUtilizationAlarmConditionThreshold and hmIfaceUtilizationAlarmRemovalThreshold.

hmDevMonStateChange.name: hmDevMonStateChange

hmSFPRxPowerChangeTrap.name: hmSFPRxPowerChangeTrap

hmSysSelftestRebootOnErrorTrap.name: hmSysSelftestRebootOnErrorTrap
hmSysSelftestRebootOnErrorTrap.description: This trap is sent when the agent wants to reboot due to an internal circumstance.

hmTemperatureTrap.name: hmTemperatureTrap

hmAutoconfigAdapterTrap.name: hmAutoconfigAdapterTrap

hmRelayDuplicateIPTrap.name: hmRelayDuplicateIPTrap
hmRelayDuplicateIPTrap.description: This trap reports the detection of a duplicate ip address by the relay agent.

hmSNTPTrap.name: hmSNTPTrap
hmSNTPTrap.description: This trap reports SNTP error conditions. For a list of possible error conditions refer to hmNetSNTPOperStatus.

hmNetACDNotification.name: hmNetACDNotification
hmNetACDNotification.description: This trap reports an address conflict detection.

hmConfigurationSavedTrap.name: hmConfigurationSavedTrap
hmConfigurationSavedTrap.description: This trap is sent after the configuration of the agent was successfully saved.

hmConfigurationChangedTrap.name: hmConfigurationChangedTrap
hmConfigurationChangedTrap.description: This trap is sent if the local and the running configuration doesn't match.

hmAddressRelearnDetectTrap.name: hmAddressRelearnDetectTrap

hmNTPTrap.name: hmNTPTrap

hmPortMonitorPortDisabledTrap.name: hmPortMonitorPortDisabledTrap

hmPOEModulePowerUsageOnNotification.description: This trap reports POE error condition. This Notification indicate PSE Threshold usage indication is on, the usage power is above the threshold. At least 500 msec must elapse between notifications being emitted by the same object instance.
